\begin_layout Subsection
Coordinate Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the coordinate systems used in our simulation codes is always
 difficult, especially if your memory is as bad as mine.
 So, these descriptions should help.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
GrISU Ground Coordinate System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GrISU Cherenkov files either from GrISU or from the CORSIKA I/O Reader
 use the following coordinate system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset space \hspace*{}
\length 20pt
\end_inset

x: East 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \hspace*{}
\length 20pt
\end_inset

y: South 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \hspace*{}
\length 20pt
\end_inset

z: Down 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 to form a right-handed system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
GrOptics ground coordinate system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incoming GrISU produced incoming photons are immediately transformed
 by GrOptics to the system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset space \hspace*{}
\length 20pt
\end_inset

x: East 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \hspace*{}
\length 20pt
\end_inset

y: North
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \hspace*{}
\length 20pt
\end_inset

z: up
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 forming a right-handed system.
 The telescope locations in the VERITAS GrISU configuration file use this
 coordinate system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Telescope Coordinate System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each telescope has a coordinate system with origin at the telescope rotation
 point and with z axis pointed toward the sky along the optic axis of the
 telescope.
 In stow position (DC telescopes), the z axis is horizontal and pointed
 toward the North, the y axis is down, and the x axis is toward the East.
 To point the telescope to a given location on the sky, GrOptics first rotates
 the telescope about the vertical through the azimuthal angle.
 Then, it raises the telescope about its new x axis through the elevation
 angle.
 This new coordinate system is the "telescope coordinate system".
 Prior to injection into the GTelescope class, the photons undergo a coordinate
 transformation to this telescope coordinate system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Array Coordinate System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prior to added pointing misalignments, all telescopes point to the same
 location on the sky with coordinate systems previously defined.
 The array coordinate system is similarly defined, but its origin is at
 the origin of the array.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Camera Coordinate System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For historical reasons, the camera coordinate system's y axis is a reflection
 of the y-axis of the telescope coordinate system.
 For the VERITAS telescope, stand in front of the camera with the telescope
 in stow position.
 The camera y axis is up and the camera x axis is to your right (to the
 East).
 The telescope y-axis is down; its x axis is to the right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the output tree of grOptics, the photon locations on the camera are in
 camera coordinates for all telescope types.
 I'll add an input flag later to select photon camera locations in either
 telescope or camera coordinates.
\end_layout

